You can not use `WebElement` object after page is reloaded. After the login you have to reinitiate the objects.

You can create a method where elements locating is wrapped, like this:

	public static void login(WebDriver driver, String userName, String password) {
		WebElement userNameInput = driver.findElement(By.id(&quot;username&quot;));
		userNameInput.click();
		userNameInput.sendKeys(userName);		
		WebElement passwordInput = driver.findElement(By.id(&quot;password&quot;));
		passwordInput.click();
		passwordInput.sendKeys(password);		
		WebElement loginButton = driver.findElement(By.id(&quot;login&quot;));
		loginButton.click();
	}

usage will be simply:

    login(driver, &quot;km123&quot;, &quot;pass&quot;);
    // code to verify successful login, logout if successful, reload login page if unsuccessful
    login(driver, &quot;foo&quot;, &quot;bar&quot;);
    // code to verify unsuccessful login

Cutting tests into those small methods make creating new test quite simple like building something from prefabricated pieces.

Few tips:

 - `Login`- don&#39;t name objects with first capital . Better to name objects with some  identifier like loginButton, cookiesAcceptButton, etc.
 - don&#39;t post code as image, image is for image and code formatting is for code.
 - be aware of type errors like missing quotes in `usename.sendKeys(&quot;km123);`

